    "summary": "Dr. Chris Arts currently holds the position of associate professor in Translational biomaterials research at dept. orthopedic surgery at Maastricht University Medical Centre and Dept. orthopaedic biomechanics Eindhoven University of Technology TU/e.\n\nTranslational biomaterials research is performed for bone healing, infection treatment, spinal fusion and  spinal deformity correction from R&D towards clinical implementation with focus on both mechanical performance and biological efficacy and safety of newly develop biomaterials in animal models and clinical patients. \n\nHigh resolution imaging of bone density and bone microarchitecture (HRpQCT) and imaging of the physiological bone healing proces (PET-CT and PET-MRI) are essential and my part-time appointment at Eindhoven University of Technology offers great opportunities to have adequate support in material characterisation, image analysis with Micro CT and Finite Element Analysis and mechanobiology. \n\nInfection research is research on mechanical performance and biological efficacy and safety in animal models of newly develop biomaterials / coating technology for infection treatment. Secondly, the translation towards clinical use and further assessment of efficacy and safety on these newly developed technologies in patients is studied multidisciplinary. S53P4 bioactive glass is a biomaterial with great promise that we currently investigate in mechanical, biological and clinical projects.Within the Dutch National Science Agenda project NWA DARTBAC we develop material technology to curb antimicrobial resistance to antibiotics. https://nwa-dartbac.eu  \n\nSpine research aims to develop a new methodology to operate scoliosis patients and offer them 3D deformity correction over time, spinal growth and preservation of spine mobility. furthermore we perform research on optimisation of spinal fusion surgery results by developing new biomaterials and design new 3d printed cages. https://prosperosinterreg.eu \n\nThe ongoing development of Maastricht and Chemelot campuses in our area and the link to high tech campus and brain port in Eindhoven with 3-D print infrastructure that is being regionally developed in the south of the Netherlands is the specific area I see my future development as a scientist. In vivo imaging in patients using HRpQCT, PET-CT and PET-MR and FEA modeling will be important supporting facilities required in this transition.\n\nhttps://www.researchgate.net/profile/Jacobus_Arts",
